(3001, '0D58DE43-0105-4401-A8FC-E7488DA87A25', 'I have 2 beautiful boys.  I don’t what I’d do if they were black. I don’t know how I’d help them navigate our world.   My kids are safe and won’t be subjected to murder for jogging, walking in the park, passing a phony $20, hanging with their friends, or anything else.   They are asking me what’s wrong with me as I’m a hot mess right now - and I don’t know how to talk to them about all this.  They are smart and culturally sensitive kids - but I need to get more raw and truthful with them and I’m not sure this is the time.  But if not now - when?  The orange turd is literally the worst human being ever and yet his voice is  what they hear.  They ask me questions I can’t answer anymore.  They have a privilege kids of color don’t have - but I’ve tried to explain that their success and joy in life is due to their character and effort.  This isn’t true - but I wanted them to believe it because perhaps they could help will it into reality.  We live in a suburban bubble - which is great for bike riding and many other things - but not for teaching the life lessons they need right now.  We’ve marched before - but that always feels good in the moment yet nothing changes.  But if I’m lost and confused - how do parents with boys of color deal with this crap and life in general?? (not singling out boys vs girls  - but I have 2 sons) Parenting is never easy - but this burden is more than I can fathom.', 'Nitzan', 'David', '2020-05-30T09:27:48.407825'),
